00:04:48.260 --> 00:04:51.910
And I'm talking about
my home team here.

00:04:51.910 --> 00:04:55.890
I was vested interest in the moon,
obviously, but I think of the moon

00:04:55.890 --> 00:04:58.960
of the cornerstone of
understanding how planets work.

00:04:58.960 --> 00:05:01.150
We can learn about a lot
by studying the Earth.

00:05:01.150 --> 00:05:03.510
That's why we go out and
study lava flows in Hawaii.

00:05:03.510 --> 00:05:05.680
How do planets work?

00:05:05.680 --> 00:05:08.480
But the Earth is not the
best example of a planet.

00:05:08.480 --> 00:05:11.760 position:56%
We have our lovely atmosphere, we've
got water that erodes the surface.

00:05:11.760 --> 00:05:15.830
If you look at the other planets,
large objects in our solar system,

00:05:15.830 --> 00:05:18.380
outside on the table outside in
the hall, I encourage you to pick

00:05:18.380 --> 00:05:20.980
up the information about the
new Verizon's mission which flew

00:05:20.980 --> 00:05:24.220
by Pluto several months back.

00:05:24.220 --> 00:05:27.600
Those images of Pluto reveal a
world that's unlike anything,

00:05:27.600 --> 00:05:29.220
at least I expected.

00:05:29.220 --> 00:05:32.480 position:56%
But our understanding of the moon is
what helps us interpret the record

00:05:32.480 --> 00:05:35.840 position:56%
of the surface of Pluto, of Mercury,

00:05:35.840 --> 00:05:38.770
ultimately of any object
in the solar system.

00:05:38.770 --> 00:05:40.850
My mind goes back to
understanding what's going

00:05:40.850 --> 00:05:43.050
on on the lunar surface.

00:05:43.050 --> 00:05:44.650
Because the moon is
close to the Earth,

00:05:44.650 --> 00:05:47.190
it took the astronauts
three days to get there.

00:05:47.190 --> 00:05:49.510
It is a neighbor.

00:05:49.510 --> 00:05:52.330
I like to think of the moon
as sort of the Earth's attic.

00:05:52.330 --> 00:05:54.870
It's where the ancient record
of the inter-solar system,

00:05:54.870 --> 00:05:57.070
our corner of the solar
system, is recorded.

00:05:57.070 --> 00:06:00.090
In the rocks on the
surface of the moon.

00:06:00.090 --> 00:06:03.740
And because we have the
six Apollo landing sites,

00:06:03.740 --> 00:06:05.050
we have those successful missions

00:06:05.050 --> 00:06:07.380
that brought rocks
back to the Earth.

00:06:07.380 --> 00:06:10.000
Those samples tell us
something very important

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:14.510
about how the moon evolved, and by
association we can use those rocks

00:06:14.510 --> 00:06:19.070
to understand how the moon evolved
and how planets work in general.

00:06:19.070 --> 00:06:20.470
But one of the things that we get

00:06:20.470 --> 00:06:22.300
from our mission that's
orbiting the moon right now,

00:06:22.300 --> 00:06:25.970
The Lunar Reconnaissance Orbiter,
is the context for those samples.

00:06:25.970 --> 00:06:29.350
A rock is a wonderful thing,
but a rock with context

00:06:29.350 --> 00:06:32.910
where you know exactly where it
came from, where it's history is

00:06:32.910 --> 00:06:34.880
that you can use to tell a story,

00:06:34.880 --> 00:06:37.180
tells a lot about how
a planet works.

00:06:37.180 --> 00:06:39.710
And so what I'm going to
talk about in the latter half

00:06:39.710 --> 00:06:42.710
of my presentation, is the
context of some samples

00:06:42.710 --> 00:06:44.590
that we got form Apollo 17

00:06:44.590 --> 00:06:47.950
and how the new data we have helps
us better understand what those

00:06:47.950 --> 00:06:49.250
rocks are telling us.

00:06:49.250 --> 00:06:52.360
We're here and building
a facility that's devoted

00:06:52.360 --> 00:06:55.150
to the history of the written word.

00:06:55.150 --> 00:06:58.750
The rocks, I like to think of
rocks as kind of like little books.

00:06:58.750 --> 00:07:02.210
It's up to us to understand
what those books are telling us.

00:07:02.210 --> 00:07:06.250
A rock without context is like one
of the middle books of a volume.

00:07:06.250 --> 00:07:08.650
If you took book three
of Harry Potter,

00:07:08.650 --> 00:07:11.080
well you don't know what
went on on either sides.

00:07:11.080 --> 00:07:14.010
But if you have context, the
full volume of an encyclopedia

00:07:14.010 --> 00:07:17.340
or Harry Potter, you get a
better sense of the whole story.

00:07:17.340 --> 00:07:19.910
And so when we get the
context of these samples,

00:07:19.910 --> 00:07:22.110
whether it's through the images
the Apollo astronauts took

00:07:22.110 --> 00:07:26.890
or those images in the context of
the entire planet and the globe

00:07:26.890 --> 00:07:29.260
of the moon, that tells us
something very important

00:07:29.260 --> 00:07:31.290
about how the moon works.

00:07:31.290 --> 00:07:33.970
So that's my preamble about why
I think the moon is important.

00:07:33.970 --> 00:07:37.620
Hopefully, if you're
convinced, that's wonderful.

00:07:37.620 --> 00:07:41.430
If not, well let's at least enjoy
talking about some of the things

00:07:41.430 --> 00:07:43.330
that I do on a daily basis.

00:07:43.330 --> 00:07:47.760
This is one of those awesome
external rocket camera footage

00:07:47.760 --> 00:07:50.240
that we get from rocket launches.

00:07:50.240 --> 00:07:54.090
This was in the late
afternoon of June 18th, 2009.

00:07:54.090 --> 00:07:56.270
The launch of the Lunar
Reconnaissance Orbiter.

00:07:56.270 --> 00:07:58.710
This is in the pre
hi-def day, by the way.

00:07:58.710 --> 00:08:00.250
I sort of shutter to show this.

00:08:00.250 --> 00:08:03.220
But it is still pretty
spectacular, the launch of LRO.

00:08:03.220 --> 00:08:06.410
Now, LRO has been at the
moon for over seven years.

00:08:06.410 --> 00:08:08.830
That feels like it's gone
by pretty quickly to me.

00:08:08.830 --> 00:08:12.280
But the seven years that LRO has
been at the moon is important,

00:08:12.280 --> 00:08:14.780
and not just because that's seven
years of funding for someone

00:08:14.780 --> 00:08:16.330
like me to work on the mission.

00:08:16.330 --> 00:08:18.160
But it's seven years of
studying the moon in a way

00:08:18.160 --> 00:08:22.320
that we've never been
able to do before.

00:08:22.320 --> 00:08:26.430
Oftentimes, what we do in planetary
science is we go to a new object,

00:08:26.430 --> 00:08:30.280
we go to Mars, we either fly by
it as we did in the case of Pluto

00:08:30.280 --> 00:08:32.260
or we orbit it very shortly.

00:08:32.260 --> 00:08:35.470
What's happened at Mars with our
long duration of orbital missions

00:08:35.470 --> 00:08:37.240
and indeed now what's
happening at the moon,

00:08:37.240 --> 00:08:38.830
is we're not measuring the moon

00:08:38.830 --> 00:08:40.900
in ways we've never
been able to do before.

00:08:40.900 --> 00:08:43.300
We're actually able to
[inaudible] the changes that occur

00:08:43.300 --> 00:08:44.600
on the surface of the moon.

00:08:44.600 --> 00:08:45.920
We're finding new impact craters

00:08:45.920 --> 00:08:48.330
that have formed in
the last seven years.

00:08:48.330 --> 00:08:51.130
Now if you're like me, first
of all I apologize for that,

00:08:51.130 --> 00:08:54.700
but if you're like me you go to
Google Earth and maybe you look

00:08:54.700 --> 00:08:56.490
at your neighborhood, and
you use the little slider

00:08:56.490 --> 00:08:57.910 position:56%
to see what your neighborhood looked

00:08:57.910 --> 00:08:59.500
like ten years ago,
twenty years ago.

00:08:59.500 --> 00:09:01.660
We can do that for
areas of the moon now.

00:09:01.660 --> 00:09:06.450
We can see images from eight years
ago, not eight, six years ago,

00:09:06.450 --> 00:09:08.860
and images taken yesterday
and compare them

00:09:08.860 --> 00:09:10.460
and actually see changes
that are occurring

00:09:10.460 --> 00:09:11.940
on the surface of the moon.

00:09:11.940 --> 00:09:13.410
Why is that important?

00:09:13.410 --> 00:09:15.680
Well, before LRO we
had no idea the rate

00:09:15.680 --> 00:09:17.340
at which the surface
of the moon changed.

00:09:17.340 --> 00:09:19.110
And as I said before,
our understanding

00:09:19.110 --> 00:09:21.410
of the moon is what we use
to leverage our understanding

00:09:21.410 --> 00:09:23.040
of all other objects
in the solar system.

00:09:23.040 --> 00:09:24.850
So when we learn that
the moon is dynamic,

00:09:24.850 --> 00:09:27.930
it's changing at a very slow
rate but still changing,

00:09:27.930 --> 00:09:31.380 position:56%
that tells us something important
about what's happening on asteroids,

00:09:31.380 --> 00:09:34.210
Mercury, throughout
the solar system.

00:09:34.210 --> 00:09:36.550
Indeed, one of the most
interesting implications relevant

00:09:36.550 --> 00:09:39.400
to the Apollo landing sites
is those beautiful footprints.

00:09:39.400 --> 00:09:41.230
We're all familiar with
the image from Apollo 11

00:09:41.230 --> 00:09:42.530
of Buzz Aldrin's boot print.

00:09:42.530 --> 00:09:44.020
And the thought for years was

00:09:44.020 --> 00:09:46.920
that that boot print would be
visible for millions of years.

00:09:46.920 --> 00:09:49.240
It turns out that the rate
of change, the new impacts

00:09:49.240 --> 00:09:52.390
and the turning of the surface of
the moon is happening much faster

00:09:52.390 --> 00:09:54.690
than we expected and that boot
print may disappear in the scale

00:09:54.690 --> 00:09:56.240
of 100,000 years, not
a million years.

00:09:56.240 --> 00:09:59.280
Now that may not seem all
that important but again,

00:09:59.280 --> 00:10:02.370 position:56%
we are using the moon as a natural
laboratory to understand the process

00:10:02.370 --> 00:10:03.770
that are affecting
all of the planets

00:10:03.770 --> 00:10:06.190
in the solar system,
including the Earth.

00:10:06.190 --> 00:10:09.230
So LRO, and I'm going to
show a lot of pictures today.

00:10:09.230 --> 00:10:11.110
Because pictures are
worth 1,000 words

00:10:11.110 --> 00:10:13.710
but LRO has many, many instruments.

00:10:13.710 --> 00:10:15.600
Seven instruments, in fact.

00:10:15.600 --> 00:10:20.990
When LRO was launched in
2009, there was a plan

00:10:20.990 --> 00:10:23.620
that we would eventually
send humans and robots back

00:10:23.620 --> 00:10:25.040
to the surface of the moon.

00:10:25.040 --> 00:10:26.910
And so we wanted a
Reconnaissance mission.

00:10:26.910 --> 00:10:30.040
A mission that would find the safe
and interesting landing sites.

00:10:30.040 --> 00:10:33.010
That would tell us where to go and
how to stay at the moon safely.

00:10:33.010 --> 00:10:36.660
And so these instruments were
selected to find safe places

00:10:36.660 --> 00:10:40.470
to basically pave the way for
human exploration into deep space.

00:10:40.470 --> 00:10:42.840
They're also selected
to help us find places

00:10:42.840 --> 00:10:45.430
where you might find water
or [inaudible] at the moon.

00:10:45.430 --> 00:10:48.660
One of the objectives was
originally to send humans

00:10:48.660 --> 00:10:49.960
to the moon to live off the land.

00:10:49.960 --> 00:10:52.830
And one of the ways to do that
is to not have to bring all

00:10:52.830 --> 00:10:54.490
of the water and oxygen with you.

00:10:54.490 --> 00:10:56.820
So we wanted to find places
where we could get water

00:10:56.820 --> 00:10:58.580
from the lunar surface.

00:10:58.580 --> 00:11:02.320
And so we have instruments
ranging from a radiation detector

00:11:02.320 --> 00:11:06.180
that measures how much radiation
damage a human might expect

00:11:06.180 --> 00:11:08.430
when they're traveling to the moon.

00:11:08.430 --> 00:11:14.120
We have a thermal instrument that
measures the surface temperature

00:11:14.120 --> 00:11:18.030 position:56%
of the moon, an instrument that will
measure reflected starlight that's

00:11:18.030 --> 00:11:21.230
light not form our sun, but
light from all the other stars

00:11:21.230 --> 00:11:24.420
in the galaxy that reflect
off the nice side off the moon

00:11:24.420 --> 00:11:26.940
to suggest where water might be.

00:11:26.940 --> 00:11:30.890
We have a neutron detector that can
map out where hydrogen is present,

00:11:30.890 --> 00:11:32.590
commonly in the form
of oxygen or OOH.

00:11:32.590 --> 00:11:36.740
We have a laser instrument that
measures the surface topography

00:11:36.740 --> 00:11:39.320
of the moon with a precision
greater than any object

00:11:39.320 --> 00:11:40.620
that we have in the solar system.

00:11:40.620 --> 00:11:44.370
We have the best topography, not
to sound like a future President.

00:11:44.370 --> 00:11:46.860
We have the best Topography
in the solar system

00:11:46.860 --> 00:11:50.390
at the moon thanks to
the Lola instrument.

00:11:50.390 --> 00:11:52.180
The L Rock instrument, a camera

00:11:52.180 --> 00:11:55.380
which is actually 3 different
cameras, has mapped the moon

00:11:55.380 --> 00:11:58.330
at resolutions of approximately
fifty centimeters per pixel.

00:11:58.330 --> 00:12:00.470
We're going to see a lot
of those pictures today.

00:12:00.470 --> 00:12:03.570
And a radar instrument that allows
us to peer beneath the surface.

00:12:03.570 --> 00:12:07.310
Kind of 3D glasses, x-ray
glasses to see what's going

00:12:07.310 --> 00:12:10.120
on in the first upper
meter or so of the surface.

00:12:10.120 --> 00:12:13.320
That gives us a sense of what's
happening to the lunar surface.

00:12:13.320 --> 00:12:15.510
Also, it's been used
to map out the presence

00:12:15.510 --> 00:12:18.700
of ice deposits near
the lunar poles.

00:12:18.700 --> 00:12:22.350 position:56%
So all of these instruments combined
gibe us this really incredible view

00:12:22.350 --> 00:12:24.940
of the moon that we've
never had before.

00:12:24.940 --> 00:12:26.790
Because we've been to the moon,

