We benefitted not only by
having Jack on the surface

00:24:51.140 --> 00:24:55.650
of the moon then, but also now
44 years later working with him

00:24:55.650 --> 00:24:59.220
to reanalyze what he did
on the surface of the moon

00:24:59.220 --> 00:25:02.350
on those three days in 1972.

00:25:02.350 --> 00:25:03.750
And so one of the benefits

00:25:03.750 --> 00:25:07.690
that I feel is happened strongly
today is not only he gets the right

00:25:07.690 --> 00:25:10.260
samples but he's helped
us tell that story.

00:25:10.260 --> 00:25:14.290
Again, take those stories each rock
tells us and weave a narrative.

00:25:14.290 --> 00:25:17.380
A history behind those rocks.

00:25:17.380 --> 00:25:20.700
So let's go back to why
Apollo 17 was sent to the moon

00:25:20.700 --> 00:25:23.080
and what its objectives were.

00:25:23.080 --> 00:25:26.230
Now Apollo 17 was being planned
in the early part of 1972.

00:25:26.230 --> 00:25:30.650
This was hot on the heels of
Apollo 15 but before Apollo 16,

00:25:30.650 --> 00:25:32.710
and there were five
objectives laid out.

00:25:32.710 --> 00:25:37.030
This is defined by an August panel
of leaders saying that they wanted

00:25:37.030 --> 00:25:38.480
to sample ancient lunar crust.

00:25:38.480 --> 00:25:40.870
As far from the Apollo 15
landing site as possible.

00:25:40.870 --> 00:25:45.010 position:56%
When I showed you that map of Apollo
landing sites, they all cluster

00:25:45.010 --> 00:25:47.280
in a region roughly
around the equator,

00:25:47.280 --> 00:25:50.490
but they are also very
close to one large feature.

00:25:50.490 --> 00:25:51.880
The imbrium basin.

00:25:51.880 --> 00:25:54.280
They wanted to get a landing site
as far from the imbrium basin

00:25:54.280 --> 00:25:58.010
as safely possible so that
they could gather the diversity

00:25:58.010 --> 00:25:59.490
of the lunar surface.

00:25:59.490 --> 00:26:02.720
They wanted to sample what they
thought were young volcanic rocks.

00:26:02.720 --> 00:26:06.960 position:56%
Most of the volcanic rocks that we
got back from the moon are the order

00:26:06.960 --> 00:26:09.280
of three to four billion years old.

00:26:09.280 --> 00:26:11.460
And they wanted to try to get
rocks that were younger than that.

00:26:11.460 --> 00:26:13.980
Volcanic rocks that
were younger than that.

00:26:13.980 --> 00:26:16.960 position:56%
They wanted to get improved coverage
by the orbiting command module.

00:26:16.960 --> 00:26:22.230
The command module orbited sort
of in a roughly hula hoop band

00:26:22.230 --> 00:26:24.290
around the surface of
the moon that passed

00:26:24.290 --> 00:26:25.900
over each of the landing sites.

00:26:25.900 --> 00:26:29.570
They wanted to get coverage that
improved upon the prior missions.

00:26:29.570 --> 00:26:33.600 position:56%
They wanted to be able to deploy
geophysical elements on the surface,

00:26:33.600 --> 00:26:36.310
but also in an area that
had some surface layers.

00:26:36.310 --> 00:26:39.210
They're looking for a
volcanically covered region

00:26:39.210 --> 00:26:42.450
to measure the thickness
of those volcanic layers.

00:26:42.450 --> 00:26:46.310 position:56%
And then also deploy the experiments
that would then subsequently be left

00:26:46.310 --> 00:26:49.330
on the surface of the moon
after the mission concluded.

00:26:49.330 --> 00:26:52.910
So the Apollo 17 landing site, and
there's my first typo of the day,

00:26:52.910 --> 00:26:55.940
was selected on-- this
is not an Irish spelling.

00:26:55.940 --> 00:26:58.100
This was on February 11th, 1972.

00:26:58.100 --> 00:27:01.010
So just keep in mind,
so they have had,

00:27:01.010 --> 00:27:03.980
at this point they had essentially
one year or just under a year,

00:27:03.980 --> 00:27:08.750 position:56%
ten months to plan the investigation

00:27:08.750 --> 00:27:11.340
at the Taurus-Littrow
Valley for Apollo 17.

00:27:11.340 --> 00:27:15.190
So with these five goals and the
identification of a landing site,

00:27:15.190 --> 00:27:20.640
specific traverses were identified
to address those five topics.

00:27:20.640 --> 00:27:23.600
And so using images that came
back from the Apollo 15 mission,

00:27:23.600 --> 00:27:26.160
and these prior missions
all shouted for each other.

00:27:26.160 --> 00:27:31.670
They were all imaging potential
landing sites for future missions.

00:27:31.670 --> 00:27:34.590
Five different units,
five different areas

00:27:34.590 --> 00:27:37.830
within the Taurus-Littrow
Valley here,

00:27:37.830 --> 00:27:40.040
five different units
were identified.

00:27:40.040 --> 00:27:42.370
It may be a little hard
to see in the screen here,

00:27:42.370 --> 00:27:45.250
but there is this light
debris material,

00:27:45.250 --> 00:27:49.820
this light colored unit called
the light mantel deposit

00:27:49.820 --> 00:27:51.330
that they wanted to sample.

00:27:51.330 --> 00:27:55.890
There's the dark mantel deposit
and this is a larger unit

00:27:55.890 --> 00:27:59.790
where the floor of the valley,
this dark floor of the valley,

00:27:59.790 --> 00:28:02.140
appeared to have some
kind of covering.

00:28:02.140 --> 00:28:03.440
The craters that you see

00:28:03.440 --> 00:28:05.680
on the surface all appear
to be somewhat degraded.

00:28:05.680 --> 00:28:10.050
You ever picture your lawn or
your front yard or some large area

00:28:10.050 --> 00:28:14.480
on a snowy day everything, your
wall, gets a little bit subdued.

00:28:14.480 --> 00:28:18.440
So there was this hypothesis that
there was some covering material,

00:28:18.440 --> 00:28:20.500
something covering the
floor of the valley here

00:28:20.500 --> 00:28:21.840
that they wanted to sample.

00:28:21.840 --> 00:28:25.220
They wanted to sample whatever
was below that, the subfloor.

00:28:25.220 --> 00:28:27.410
They also wanted to get
material from this unit here.

00:28:27.410 --> 00:28:29.400 position:56%
This is called the sculptured hills.

00:28:29.400 --> 00:28:30.750
This has a slightly
different texture.

00:28:30.750 --> 00:28:37.020
To use a very technical term,
lumpy, compared to these mountains

00:28:37.020 --> 00:28:39.540
to the North and South of the
valley that appear to be--

00:28:39.540 --> 00:28:44.890
to use another technical
term-- mountain like.

00:28:44.890 --> 00:28:46.860
There are these little knobs
in the sculptured hills

00:28:46.860 --> 00:28:51.190
where the [inaudible] appear
to be one large, coherent unit.

00:28:51.190 --> 00:28:53.790
So with the identification of
these five different units,

00:28:53.790 --> 00:28:56.800
traverses were identified based
on the optimal landing site

00:28:56.800 --> 00:28:59.620
in the middle of the valley
where the astronauts could drive

00:28:59.620 --> 00:29:03.330
around the valley to sample
these different materials.

00:29:03.330 --> 00:29:06.660
Just as a point of comparison, talk
about the Taurus-Littrow Valley

00:29:06.660 --> 00:29:10.570
and a little bit of scale, this
is the Grand Canyon on the Earth.

00:29:10.570 --> 00:29:14.470
This is, again, using that
amazing tool Google Earth,

00:29:14.470 --> 00:29:16.820
and this is a transect
through the Grand Canyon.

00:29:16.820 --> 00:29:19.370
So this is about 30
kilometers from end to end.

00:29:19.370 --> 00:29:25.560
Covers about a kilometer and a
half, 1.8 kilometers of relief.

00:29:25.560 --> 00:29:27.650
For comparison, this is
the Taurus-Littrow Valley,

00:29:27.650 --> 00:29:30.210
same 3 thirty kilometers across.

00:29:30.210 --> 00:29:34.040
This is two and a half, 2.3
kilometers of elevation change.

00:29:34.040 --> 00:29:37.970
So this is another important
thing to consider here.

00:29:37.970 --> 00:29:39.910
With the first Apollo
landing, Apollo 11,

00:29:39.910 --> 00:29:43.550 position:56%
they landed in what they thought was
the smoothest safest landing site,

00:29:43.550 --> 00:29:45.590
as far from hazards as they could.

00:29:45.590 --> 00:29:47.530
And of course when they
tried to land on Apollo 11,

00:29:47.530 --> 00:29:49.200
they were headed right
for a boulder field.

00:29:49.200 --> 00:29:52.120
And so Neil Armstrong had to
steer the lunar module away

00:29:52.120 --> 00:29:54.180
from those boulders.

00:29:54.180 --> 00:29:57.910
Just four years later,
they were able to land

00:29:57.910 --> 00:30:00.750
in a valley deeper
than the Grand Canyon.

00:30:00.750 --> 00:30:04.610
That's an incredible
advancement in a very short order,

00:30:04.610 --> 00:30:09.620
going from finding the safest
landing site to landing in a valley

00:30:09.620 --> 00:30:13.960
where you have towering
mountains on either side of you.

00:30:13.960 --> 00:30:17.320
That was quite the accomplishment.

00:30:17.320 --> 00:30:20.400 position:56%
Ok, so let's now look after mission.

00:30:20.400 --> 00:30:22.910
How did the-- let's
give the astronauts,

00:30:22.910 --> 00:30:25.530
let's give the Apollo
17 crew an evaluation.

00:30:25.530 --> 00:30:26.880
How did they do?

00:30:26.880 --> 00:30:32.290 position:56%
So, for those pre-flight objectives,
they were indeed able to go

00:30:32.290 --> 00:30:36.140
and sample this light mantel
deposit, this debris flow.

00:30:36.140 --> 00:30:39.590
And an interpretation
was made from--

00:30:39.590 --> 00:30:43.280
an interpretation from the origin
of this debris flow was made

00:30:43.280 --> 00:30:45.290
that material from
that tycho crater,

00:30:45.290 --> 00:30:47.090 position:56%
and I showed you that image earlier.

00:30:47.090 --> 00:30:49.700
Tycho crater is located
over 1,000 kilometers away

00:30:49.700 --> 00:30:51.500
from the Apollo 17 landing site.

00:30:51.500 --> 00:30:54.980
That objected material shot
out of that crater, landed,

00:30:54.980 --> 00:31:01.060 position:56%
hit the top of the South [inaudible]
and triggered a landslide.

00:31:01.060 --> 00:31:03.830
So the interpretation was that the
astronauts sampled this material

00:31:03.830 --> 00:31:08.410
that was estimated to be
about 100 million years old,

00:31:08.410 --> 00:31:13.180
was caused by the formation of
that crater, 1,000 kilometers away.

00:31:13.180 --> 00:31:16.270
And so this is one of the
beauties of lunar science is

00:31:16.270 --> 00:31:21.080
that you can have an event 1,000
kilometers away trigger a landslide

00:31:21.080 --> 00:31:22.920
here, and we can go and
sample that landslide

00:31:22.920 --> 00:31:24.710
and get the age of that crater.

00:31:24.710 --> 00:31:26.010
So that's handy.

00:31:26.010 --> 00:31:28.840
And as a reminder, geologists
are very interested in organiza--

00:31:28.840 --> 00:31:31.310
if you ever come to my
office, you may not think

00:31:31.310 --> 00:31:34.300
that geologists are
interested in organizing things,

00:31:34.300 --> 00:31:38.530
but indeed we like putting events
into some sort of sequence.

00:31:38.530 --> 00:31:41.310
And so getting the ages of
events is very important.

00:31:41.310 --> 00:31:44.000
So an interpretation was made
that the samples collected

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:45.380 position:56%
from this debris flow were triggered

00:31:45.380 --> 00:31:48.470
by that impact 100
million years ago.

00:31:48.470 --> 00:31:50.890
The second objective was
to sample the dark mantel,

00:31:50.890 --> 00:31:52.720
and that proved to be difficult.

00:31:52.720 --> 00:31:55.960
And again, in this
preliminary science report,

00:31:55.960 --> 00:32:01.380
interpretation was made that that
origin of that dark mantel deposit,

00:32:01.380 --> 00:32:05.190
the subdued texture of the
surface, remains one of the enigmas

00:32:05.190 --> 00:32:06.490
of the Apollo 17 missions.

00:32:06.490 --> 00:32:10.010
So we can't necessarily say
that that was addressed.

00:32:10.010 --> 00:32:12.580
Now, they did however
sample much of the subfloor.

00:32:12.580 --> 00:32:16.490
This volcanic fill that flowed
in and filled the valley.

00:32:16.490 --> 00:32:19.690 position:56%
They sampled that quite extensively.

00:32:19.690 --> 00:32:22.210
The fourth objective of
sampling the sculptured hills,

00:32:22.210 --> 00:32:26.890
now one of the last stations
on Apollo 17, station 8 here,

00:32:26.890 --> 00:32:30.650 position:56%
which the primary objective of which
was to sample the sculptured hills.

00:32:30.650 --> 00:32:32.140
But at the time it
remained uncertain.

00:32:32.140 --> 00:32:34.680
And no more is known about
the sculptured hills unit

00:32:34.680 --> 00:32:36.100
than it is indeed different.

00:32:36.100 --> 00:32:39.150
It looks different than the
[inaudible] to the North and South.

00:32:39.150 --> 00:32:40.940
And so this remained an
open question of whether

00:32:40.940 --> 00:32:44.610
or not any material from the
sculptured hills were ever sampled.

00:32:44.610 --> 00:32:47.420
And lastly, the [inaudible] and
those were sampled very well.

00:32:47.420 --> 00:32:52.210 position:56%
And as I'll show in a moment,
several stations were along the base

00:32:52.210 --> 00:32:55.960
of the [inaudible] Of course they
could not drive up the [inaudible]

00:32:55.960 --> 00:33:00.580
but instead of having to go get
the rocks, the rocks came to them.

00:33:00.580 --> 00:33:03.180
Several boulders were
observed to have rolled

00:33:03.180 --> 00:33:05.650
down the hills well
before the mission.

00:33:05.650 --> 00:33:08.490
These were boulders that were
seen in preflight images.

00:33:08.490 --> 00:33:11.190
And so they drove to the
boulders knowing that they came

00:33:11.190 --> 00:33:12.490
from somewhere up the mountain.

00:33:12.490 --> 00:33:14.630
And so those were sampled
quite well.

00:33:14.630 --> 00:33:20.290
So Now, this is the
Apollo 17 landing site.

00:33:20.290 --> 00:33:24.000
The Taurus-Littrow Valley as
imaged by the camera on LRO.

00:33:24.000 --> 00:33:30.420
Again, so this is an image
from 1972, here it is today.

